column1: For any seven consecutive day period between 1 October and 31 December 2020, will there be 200,000 or more combined total confirmed new cases of COVID-19 in the United States?
column6: ['Health']
Sigh
Sadly, Walensky was right...

According to the WHO dashboard, there have already been 129,754 cases in the US from 1 Oct to 3 Oct. Only 70,246 cases need to be reported in the next four days (this is guaranteed barring some weird data reporting fudging) for this to resolve positively. And it's only the first week of October!
Current daily infection rates are about 40k new cases per and would easily exceed 200k in a seven day period.

new combined total confirmed cases in the last 7 days is 305,412, and it looks like new cases has plateaued - not expecting much change from that for next week. That puts the chance at very close to 100% for the three month period, let alone the first week of the three month period.

Heading into October, the 7-day average for cases is 42,447 cases/day. At this rate, we would AVERAGE well over 200,000 cases each week (97,127 more to be exact). Cases would need to drop by nearly 33% in the next week for this benchmark to not be hit immediately, let alone in the 3 month period allowed here. While case counts are volatile, the current trend appears to be slightly upward, not downward, and such a drop was not observed even at the peak of shutdown measures. With many states reopening and people growing bored with many of the safety measures dictated by the CDC, this is essentially a layup at this point.

Current estimate with 100% certainty: this question will be resolved on 8 October, as confirmed new cases data for days prior to 1 October 2020 are immaterial to the resolution of this question. 1-7 October will be far above 200K.

Down to 95 again for this reason: "DSHS revised its method for reporting Total Tests, effective 9/14/2020. DSHS will now only report electronic lab results that have passed quality checks and have cleared into the state’s system of record, NEDSS, the National Electronic Disease Surveillance System. This improvement is possible due to recent upgrades to NEDSS, which now processes data more quickly. The revised methodology ensures data is fully deduplicated and that only tests that passed through the data submission quality checks are counted in Total Tests. Test submissions that error out of the system due to data quality issues will not be counted until they are successfully resubmitted and pass validation requirements. Additionally, Total Tests will no longer include faxes or aggregate counts received by various labs since there is not a timely way to complete data quality checks. "

So I'll give it a 3 in 4 chance we exceed 200k and a 1 in 4 chance we don't.

Complete turnaround from me here. I was convinced the number of cases would drop significantly when states would reach around 20k cases per million as has happened in New York, Arizona and some countries. This simply doesn't seem to hold true. Chile and Louisiana are two regions which have peaked and stabilized on a lower level, but the problem is the number of new cases daily in those regions are still higher than the threshold for 200k new cases for a given week in US. If the US cases were increasing in the same proportion as in Chile and Louisiana it will still be above 200k new cases for a week (Chile 220k new cases, Louisiana 357k new cases). Louisiana is far ahead of the curve so even if their numbers go down now (which I expect) other states is lagging behind and will keep the numbers up for the coming month. The numbers of new cases in US also went up to the highest they been for three weeks yesterday. I don't see any way for the numbers to drop to levels needed for this not to come true, so going 100% yes now.

Although I have high confidence there will be >200,000 cases in a 7 day period during the stated timeframe (past week alone had over 285K cases), I am decreasing chances a couple of percentage points due to recent revision of CDC guidelines concerning testing those exposed (and by extension many of the asymptomatic carriers). This has caused a major rift and the development of distrust in the CDC, Dept of HHS, and the WH amongst the medical and public health community in general. Couple that with the push to test less for political purposes and we may actually see a HUGE decrease in testing in the coming weeks. Most states are pushing back on these ideas, but not all of them. Way too many medical facilities also refuse to test those w/o meeting specific sx criteria which leads to missing many infections (ie: requirement of fever over 101.5 - we know now that a significant portion of COVID patients fail to develop significant fever sometimes even with moderate to severe illness.).

I'm really going against the crowd here, but I do believe it is pretty clear the pandemic is burning itself out in the US, question is if the number will drop fast enough in the month left until October. Of the four big states New York has been pretty stable since May with low numbers. Florida went from 11-12 000 new cases per day in the middle of July to around 3 000 now and is still dropping. Texas went from 10 000 cases daily in middle of July to around 5 000 and is still dropping albeit slower than Florida. California is behind the three others on the curve, but not that far behind and I do expect the numbers to drop from the 5 500 daily new cases (top in end of July with 10 000+) but probably with some small spikes on a given day or week. I could go into detail about other states (Georgia ahead of curve, Ohio likely behind) but I do think how the big four does will tell the story whether US will see the numbers drop below 200 000 weekly.

For this to be achieved, we would need a 7-day average to remain below 28,571.4 cases. The average hasn't been this low since mid-June, and while it is likely that cases will continue trending down and the average may, in fact, drop below this for the entire October-December range, this question requires only that one week meet the 200,000 cases mark. Children are returning to school en masse, several large gatherings have occurred in recent weeks that drew attendees from around the country, and testing of asymptomatic people has been dismissed by the CDC. With all this in mind, I believe it is more likely the cases will increase than decrease at least for a time. A previous Monte Carlo simulation assuming an average around 40,000 put the likelihood of a single week greater than 200,000 is around 90%, I think it is slightly less likely now than then but I see no reason to decrease my projection by a significant amount.

Restating forecast. Yes 200k cases in a week is 28k cases per day which seems low at the moment. However this forecast period is for October, a period starting 3 months from now. The current levels will cause behaviour change between now and then. In Europe cases have dropped back a long way after 3 months. Even if there is a US peak to come it’s unlikely to still be 3 months away and there is a lot of time for cases to plateau as they have done in other areas. Let’s assume the US compares to the whole EU (broadly the same population), and assume the US follows the EU with a lag of 3 months. The EU is about 3 months past a peak and has plateaued around 5k cases per day, which is 25k per week. Close the the 28k needed for this forecast but still lower. Restating that this is a risky, borderline forecast, but the probability of hitting 200k in a week between October and December is lower than it is in the next 3 months. Of course the US election is early November giving time for any infections generated on that day to manifest, and for pre election campaigning to spread the virus, but I genuinely think people will be more careful by then. But will have to revisit view on this interaction as well as the likelihood of people travelling for thanksgiving. Sticking with 30pc for now.

This is likely to rise even if those states impose new lockdowns, since new cases go back around 2-3 weeks from point of infection. -U.S. seems to dealing with this at the state level and unlikely that will change. U.S. will likely not try to impose restrictions in states that are contributing heavily to the national total, for structural (state autonomy) and political reasons. -A second peak is likely prior to 1 Oct, which will lead to public pressure for renewed lockdowns, and the lockdowns will come but much later than if we had a centralized system like China. -(Outcome of U.S. election on 8 Nov is unlikely to affect this dynamic.) -Thus I believe that second peak is coming, and it can be equal to or higher than the first, but it will come sooner than 1 Oct. -There will be pressure to keep schools closed during a renewed 2-3 month lockdown period. -These factors suggest that only if we have a *third* ramp up period and peak between 1 Oct and 31 Dec, can the question have a "yes" answer. -Uptick to next uptick was about three months. If pattern repeats, uptick of third wave will be about mid Sept. -So, will this third uptick, assuming it happens in mid Sept., lead to a peak as high as the first? -Looking at 1918 city-by-city stats, no city has this pattern of a third peak (if there is one) as high as the first. This is a tough one for the following reasons. The likely scenario wrt mitigation efforts is that they will be moderately effective. Right now, on April 18 we are getting roughly 30,000 new cases a day. Given the current testing problem in the US, that is surely a severe under count. Let's suppose it is off by an order of magnitude, and we have 300,000 new cases a day. Since some of the 30,000 cases per day self-present and are not picked up by testing, that suggests many cases with moderate symptoms. Those with mild symptoms self-quarantine and/or do not infect people now given the lockdown. Some people we know have no symptoms and would only get identified if they were randomly tested. So, suppose we now have 300,000 cases per day, or 2.1 million per week. If that is the case, it really depends on whether we are testing enough people in the Fall of 2021. I think testing will increase, not because the Federal government wants more testing, but because there will be demand for testing and antibody testing that will increase the test supply. If we have sufficient testing, I think we could have a 7 day period with over 300,000 cases. My analysis suggests there will be that many new cases, but my uncertainty is whether there will be that many tests.

If we loosen up by June and July and cases spike up to a second surge we might be back in lockdown by then. The testing should be better so hopefully if people are out and about we can manage the infection rate better. Who knows?
